arge"></a></div>SEGGER RTT</div></div></div>
<p>SEGGER's Real Time Transfer (RTT) is a technology for interactive user I=
/O in embedded applications.
It combines the advantages of SWO and semihosting at very high performance.=
<br>
With RTT, it is possible to output information from the target microcontrol=
ler as well as send input to the application at a very high speed
without affecting the target's real time behavior.<br>
SEGGER RTT can be used with any <a target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noop=
ener" class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://www.segger.com/products/debug=
-probes/j-link/?mtm_campaign=3Dkb&amp;mtm_kwd=3DRTT">J-Link model</a> and a=
ny supported target processor that allows background memory access,
i.e. Cortex-M and RX targets.<br>
RTT supports multiple channels in both directions, up to the host and down =
to the target,
which can be used for different purposes and provide the most possible free=
dom to the user.<br>
The default implementation uses one channel per direction, which are meant =
for printable terminal input and output.
With the <a href=3D"https://kb.segger.com/J-Link_RTT_Viewer" title=3D"J-Lin=
k RTT Viewer">J-Link RTT Viewer</a> this channel can be used for multiple "=
virtual" terminals,
allowing to print to multiple windows (e.g. one for standard output, one fo=
r error output, one for debugging output)
with just one target buffer.
An additional up (to host) channel can for example be used to send profilin=
g or event tracing data
(e.g. for <a target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener" class=3D"externa=
l text" href=3D"https://www.segger.com/products/development-tools/systemvie=
w/?mtm_campaign=3Dkb&amp;mtm_kwd=3DRTT">SEGGER SystemView</a>).
</p>
